Claim (i) is clear;
      to prove (ii), note that, if Y is the union of smooth divisors, then the rational Hodge structure \operatorname {Gr}_k^W(\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})) is the quotient of a sub-object of a Hodge structure of weight n+k, namely
               \operatorname {H}^{n-k}(\widetilde {Y}^n,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \mathbb {Q}(-k).

The claim (*)_0 is always true. Assume (*)_r, and let us prove (*)_{r+1}. We can suppose that 0\leqslant r\leqslant r_0. We have a diagram
\usepackage {amsmath} \usepackage {amssymb} \usepackage {tikz-cd} \begin {tikzcd} E_r(K,W) \ar [r,"d_r"] & E_r(K,W) \ar [r,"d_r"] & E_r(K,W) \\E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [r] \ar [u,hook] & E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [r] \ar [u,hook] & E_r(F^pK,W) \ar [u,hook,swap,"i"] \end {tikzcd}
and the image of the vertical inclusions is F_\mathrm {rec}^p(E_r(K,W)). Since i is injective,
\begin {aligned} F_\mathrm {rec}^p(E_{r+1}(K,W)) &= \operatorname {Im}\Big ( \operatorname {Ker} \big (F_\mathrm {rec}^pE_r(K,W)\xrightarrow {d_r}E_r(K,W) \big ) \to E_{r+1}(K,W) \Big ) \\&= \operatorname {Im}\Big ( \operatorname {Ker}\big ( E_r(F^pK,W)\xrightarrow {d_r}E_r(F^pK,W) \big ) \to E_{r+1}(K,W) \Big ) \\&= \operatorname {Im}\big ( E_{r+1}(F^pK,W) \to E_{r+1}(K,W) \big ). \end {aligned}
If r<r_0, then d_r is strictly compatible with F_\mathrm {rec}, whence d_rE_r(K,W)\cap E_r(F^pK,W) = d_rE_r(F^pK,W) and E_{r+1}(F^pK,W) thus injects into E_{r+1}(K,W). This proves (*)_{r+1}.

